1
00:00:05,706 --> 00:00:09,106
The Infernal Affairs screenplay
is rich in content,

2
00:00:09,676 --> 00:00:13,926
so we could have many,
many sequels if we wanted.

3
00:00:14,615 --> 00:00:16,725
But that all depends on the box office,

4
00:00:17,150 --> 00:00:21,400
since that's what lets you
go on making sequels.

5
00:00:25,759 --> 00:00:28,279
ANTHONY WONG:
It's very seldom

6
00:00:28,729 --> 00:00:34,059
that you get to do
a monologue for over a minute.

7
00:00:34,902 --> 00:00:41,232
You talk to yourself like a fool.
That actually takes a lot of skill.

8
00:00:42,209 --> 00:00:44,819
Because...
you want the audience to see--

9
00:00:45,279 --> 00:00:49,379
you want a kind of intensity.

10
00:00:50,050 --> 00:00:56,349
I'm talking to this other guy, describing
something I saw the other day.

11
00:00:57,291 --> 00:01:02,391
I'm speaking calmly,
but what I'm saying needs to be scary.

12
00:01:03,163 --> 00:01:08,963
To make the audience feel
that scariness is a real skill.

13
00:01:09,836 --> 00:01:11,506
Anybody can speak.
You just spit out the words.

14
00:01:11,838 --> 00:01:13,008
You can just read
whatever's on the page.

15
00:01:13,240 --> 00:01:15,490
SIU FAI MAK: In the beginning,

16
00:01:15,909 --> 00:01:18,629
Wong Chi Shing and Han Sam
are good friends.

17
00:01:19,179 --> 00:01:21,869
Han Sam is a polite man.

18
00:01:22,482 --> 00:01:26,202
Sure, he's a gang leader,
but he's content, not too ambitious,

19
00:01:26,787 --> 00:01:33,057
and he never worried much about
committing atrocities in his line of work.

20
00:01:33,994 --> 00:01:37,944
He pretty much joined the triad
just to make a living.

21
00:01:38,599 --> 00:01:40,379
It is his destiny.

22
00:01:41,735 --> 00:01:50,414
As for Mr. Wong, everyone thinks
of him as a loyal father figure.

23
00:01:51,745 --> 00:01:56,085
He hates bad guys,
and he stays pretty calm.

24
00:01:56,783 --> 00:02:05,983
By contrast, we wonder why
Officer Wong changed so drastically.

25
00:02:07,527 --> 00:02:10,717
He never used to be calm
by any means.

26
00:02:11,264 --> 00:02:13,634
In fact, he was downright
cruel in the past.

27
00:02:14,067 --> 00:02:17,787
Actually, he always meant
to be a good man,

28
00:02:18,538 --> 00:02:24,278
but he chose to ignore proper procedure,
to do things his own way.

29
00:02:28,749 --> 00:02:34,228
ERIC TSANG: Sam is the least
ambitious one in infernal Affairs.

30
00:02:35,088 --> 00:02:41,708
He is a person with a traditional mindset,
a common person in the world.

31
00:02:44,998 --> 00:02:49,447
A gang leader is always
a gang leader, period.

32
00:02:50,170 --> 00:02:54,390
He should never have considered
usurping the gang leader's position.

33
00:02:55,042 --> 00:02:57,652
SIU FAI MAK:
We don't learn everything there is

34
00:02:58,111 --> 00:03:01,101
to know about Sam in Infernal Affairs.

35
00:03:02,783 --> 00:03:08,143
Sam is a very emotionally reserved
character in Infernal Affairs.

36
00:03:08,955 --> 00:03:11,475
Whenever he appears, he presents
himself strictly as a gang leader.

37
00:03:11,925 --> 00:03:17,255
He shows authority, gives orders,
and breaks a few eggshells when needed.

38
00:03:20,634 --> 00:03:22,884
At one point,
I thought of having a scene

39
00:03:23,303 --> 00:03:27,613
where Sam has to pick up the eggshells!

40
00:03:28,508 --> 00:03:31,258
When you finish a meal,
somebody has to clean up the mess!

41
00:03:31,745 --> 00:03:39,955
As an audience member, ! want to
find out what kind of person he is.

42
00:03:41,188 --> 00:03:45,938
Not just as an audience member--
I myself want to know too!

43
00:03:48,261 --> 00:03:53,771
In real life,
there are real gang leaders,

44
00:03:54,634 --> 00:03:58,094
and it's understandable we would be
curious how they behave.

45
00:03:58,705 --> 00:04:05,765
Does he do his own laundry?
You know, that kind of mundane stuff.

46
00:04:34,241 --> 00:04:41,570
CARINA LAU: Mary is a clever lady,
but she's also very traditional.

47
00:04:42,716 --> 00:04:46,526
She always follows her husband.

48
00:04:47,120 --> 00:04:53,630
She takes it for granted that if
her husband is good, she will be happy.

49
00:04:54,628 --> 00:04:59,168
For any such lady, her life typically
revolves around her husband.

50
00:04:59,900 --> 00:05:01,599
She does whatever her husband says.

51
00:05:01,902 --> 00:05:05,092
She concludes that, since her husband
is so great, "Why should he be a follower?

52
00:05:05,639 --> 00:05:07,659
My husband should
be the gang leader."

53
00:05:08,041 --> 00:05:10,671
In my opinion,
that's what you'd expect of a woman.

54
00:05:19,986 --> 00:05:22,796
In infernal Affairs tl,
I pictured the first scene

55
00:05:23,623 --> 00:05:25,263
showing Lau Kin Ming walking
down the street

56
00:05:26,960 --> 00:05:28,739
from Monkok to Tsimshatsui.

57
00:05:31,565 --> 00:05:34,785
Then he shoots.

58
00:05:35,802 --> 00:05:41,252
I don't know why, but for the whole movie,
it's the first scene I always remember.

59
00:05:42,075 --> 00:05:49,635
We have Lau Kin Ming taking Mary's
clothes--Mary being played by Carina Lau.

60
00:05:50,750 --> 00:05:56,700
Ngai Kun, gang leader in Ngai families.

61
00:05:57,591 --> 00:06:04,951
This whole circuit that Edison Chen
walked, I wanted it perfect.

62
00:06:06,032 --> 00:06:13,772
Whatever he was doing--walking,
making expressions, holding a gun--

63
00:06:14,908 --> 00:06:21,618
l wanted Lau Kin Ming to do
everything perfectly.

64
00:06:22,682 --> 00:06:27,312
The manner of firing the gun,
the manner of walking--

65
00:06:28,054 --> 00:06:32,833
both needed to be perfect.

66
00:06:33,593 --> 00:06:40,303
I feel every scene has a characteristic.

67
00:06:41,501 --> 00:06:45,541
EDISON CHEN:
I feel Lau Kin Ming had

68
00:06:46,206 --> 00:06:51,036
many good scenes to perform
in this second installment.

69
00:06:51,845 --> 00:06:55,035
I can't say no one ever cared
for my character,

70
00:06:55,548 --> 00:07:04,518
but he had the feeling of being
a lone wolf during his childhood.

71
00:07:05,825 --> 00:07:11,275
After talking with Felix,
the screenwriter,

72
00:07:12,132 --> 00:07:14,852
l would go home
and ponder these things.

73
00:07:15,502 --> 00:07:22,012
was thinking how I could incorporate
my own experiences into the role,

74
00:07:23,043 --> 00:07:26,323
so that I would remember
the feeling when I was acting--

75
00:07:26,913 --> 00:07:33,303
I could feel the emotions
and invest them into the performance.

76
00:07:34,254 --> 00:07:37,714
I find that really helped me a lot.

77
00:07:38,258 --> 00:07:43,238
Before I ever read the script,
I made a point of telling myself

78
00:07:44,030 --> 00:07:53,000
everyone considers Mary to be
someone with authority and presence.

79
00:07:54,507 --> 00:07:57,497
But after seeing the script,
I concluded that

80
00:07:58,044 --> 00:08:05,104
Mary should be a person
who is graceful and polite.

81
00:08:06,219 --> 00:08:13,308
She would speak differently
when facing different people.

82
00:08:14,561 --> 00:08:17,781
She is a woman of taste.

83
00:08:18,298 --> 00:08:20,378
Since she runs her own
music and electronics store,

84
00:08:20,767 --> 00:08:22,847
she knows a great deal
about music and about stereos.

85
00:08:23,203 --> 00:08:26,772
She's a woman who knows
a thing or two about life.

86
00:08:27,540 --> 00:08:33,370
I think that Mary's attitude towards
Lau Kin Ming is pure and direct.

87
00:08:34,246 --> 00:08:41,217
She just appreciates
this boy very much.

88
00:08:42,255 --> 00:08:46,355
She felt that he was clever,
ambitious, and loyal.

89
00:08:49,629 --> 00:08:55,899
Carina Lau is a nice lady.

90
00:08:56,836 --> 00:09:07,126
Most of the girls
l know are young and lovely.

91
00:09:11,251 --> 00:09:15,231
Working with Carina Lau,
I cannot just be myself

92
00:09:15,889 --> 00:09:18,669
because the feeling is different.

93
00:09:19,125 --> 00:09:25,775
The way Carina Lau smokes,
the way she carries herself--

94
00:09:26,800 --> 00:09:29,290
all she has to do is look at you,

95
00:09:29,702 --> 00:09:33,482
and you want to sit up straight
and speak clearly.

96
00:09:34,074 --> 00:09:38,434
So even walking should not be done
the normal way Edison Chen does it.

97
00:09:39,145 --> 00:09:43,275
He should be more mature,
to match her mode of conduct.

98
00:10:02,068 --> 00:10:03,617
CHAPMAN TO:
In infernal Affairs lil,

99
00:10:03,937 --> 00:10:06,487
we assume that Crazy Keung
is in his 30s.

100
00:10:06,906 --> 00:10:10,415
That puts Crazy Keung in his 20s
in Infernal Affairs It.

101
00:10:11,044 --> 00:10:14,084
At the beginning,
the director of movie thought that

102
00:10:14,581 --> 00:10:16,751
I needed to look like
a young Crazy Keung,

103
00:10:17,150 --> 00:10:19,459
so he wanted me to lose weight.

104
00:10:19,886 --> 00:10:23,366
Then I lost about 20 pounds
for the part.

105
00:10:23,923 --> 00:10:26,793
I lost weight and took care
of the outward appearance,

106
00:10:27,293 --> 00:10:32,453
but now I had to take care
of my internal state, my behavior.

107
00:10:33,266 --> 00:10:37,986
We had in mind from the start
the sort of person who never grows up,

108
00:10:38,705 --> 00:10:42,955
who never grows in his intelligence.

109
00:10:43,643 --> 00:10:47,103
No matter what he goes through,
he never learns anything.

110
00:10:47,714 --> 00:10:49,644
We took Crazy Keung
to be such a person.

111
00:10:50,016 --> 00:10:54,236
So we let Crazy Keung
be the kind of guy

112
00:10:54,921 --> 00:10:58,671
who never polishes his behavior,

113
00:10:59,292 --> 00:11:01,902
who never grows in his understanding.

114
00:11:02,529 --> 00:11:07,569
In fact, Chan Wing Yan and I
had a complex relationship,

115
00:11:08,501 --> 00:11:12,341
because many people don't realize

116
00:11:13,006 --> 00:11:16,986
that Crazy Keung was a show-off
who liked to flash his stuff.

117
00:11:17,644 --> 00:11:20,254
You can tell by his constantly
changing styles during the movie.

118
00:11:20,747 --> 00:11:29,007
Maybe you can pick up on the fact
that this ordinary valet

119
00:11:30,256 --> 00:11:32,446
has a very flashy ponytail.

120
00:11:32,825 --> 00:11:35,665
If anything, he's overdressed,

121
00:11:36,129 --> 00:11:40,259
probably because Crazy Keung
is obsessed with looking handsome.

122
00:11:40,934 --> 00:11:43,274
And you do realize,
Chen really is handsome.

123
00:11:43,670 --> 00:11:49,209
Crazy Keung wants to look good,
and he sees that Chen looks good,

124
00:11:50,043 --> 00:11:55,933
so he naturally feels good about that
and becomes good friends with him.

125
00:11:56,849 --> 00:12:03,939
Chan Wing Yan is a complex person.
How can we say that?

126
00:12:05,024 --> 00:12:12,174
Because there are many things
he refused to do.

127
00:12:13,266 --> 00:12:15,516
But he has no choice--
he has to do it.

128
00:12:15,902 --> 00:12:19,622
In fact, it's very simple--
he's undercover.

129
00:12:20,206 --> 00:12:25,446
He pretty much hates the gangs,
but he has to rub shoulders with them.

130
00:12:26,279 --> 00:12:28,859
That's the heart of the conflict--

131
00:12:29,515 --> 00:12:33,295
"Il don't like you,
but I can't let you know that."

132
00:12:33,920 --> 00:12:37,550
JUN HU:
Shawn Yue, he was my subordinate.

133
00:12:38,157 --> 00:12:43,377
He was just a student who
hasn't graduated from police school.

134
00:12:44,163 --> 00:12:45,743
I like him very much.

135
00:12:46,065 --> 00:12:47,935
But once I know the relationship

136
00:12:48,301 --> 00:12:51,641
between Ngai Wing-Hau,
played by Francis Ng, and him,

137
00:12:52,205 --> 00:12:54,665
I start to be cautious of him.

138
00:12:55,108 --> 00:13:01,818
Wong Sir just took advantage
of this relationship to help Yu

139
00:13:02,882 --> 00:13:06,452
to get into Ngai Wing-Hau's "family."

140
00:13:07,053 --> 00:13:11,533
Shawn Yue was very studious.

141
00:13:12,258 --> 00:13:18,878
Whenever we were setting up lights,
or whenever he was free,

142
00:13:19,899 --> 00:13:23,649
he would ask me questions like
what should he do as an actor,

143
00:13:24,237 --> 00:13:30,156
what should he study,
should he go to school?

144
00:13:31,044 --> 00:13:35,264
He asked me about that kind of thing--
what should he be paying attention to.

145
00:13:35,982 --> 00:13:42,812
We had good communication,
so I didn't treat him like an idol.

146
00:13:43,856 --> 00:13:47,516
I still think he is
a hard-working person.

147
00:13:48,127 --> 00:14:02,817
In fact, Chan Wing Yan's background
is very complex. He's a gang member.

148
00:14:04,944 --> 00:14:10,894
But he followed his mother's name

149
00:14:11,784 --> 00:14:15,704
because he didn't want to have
any relationship with the triads.

150
00:14:18,257 --> 00:14:19,516
So he came out with his mother
and became a policeman

151
00:14:21,627 --> 00:14:26,786
because he wanted
to escape from the triads.

152
00:14:27,600 --> 00:14:33,370
However, he is a triad,
unfortunately, so he could not do it.

153
00:14:34,240 --> 00:14:44,180
Moreover, he had blood ties
with these people in the triads,

154
00:14:45,618 --> 00:14:52,948
which was beyond his control.

155
00:14:59,899 --> 00:15:03,649
FRANCIS NG:
Wing-Hau was a nice person,

156
00:15:04,270 --> 00:15:11,569
but he was a member of the triad.

157
00:15:12,678 --> 00:15:16,248
Members of triads
fall into two categories--

158
00:15:16,849 --> 00:15:19,399
people with family ties to the triad,
and people without family ties.

159
00:15:19,852 --> 00:15:21,932
He had a blood relationship
with these people.

160
00:15:22,288 --> 00:15:27,068
He was graceful,
calm, peaceful, and generous.

161
00:15:30,830 --> 00:15:35,050
I think he could easily have been
an entrepreneur or a politician,

162
00:15:35,735 --> 00:15:42,125
but he was tied to the triads.

163
00:15:43,075 --> 00:15:48,905
I guess it was a sensitive matter
in society.

164
00:15:49,849 --> 00:15:53,599
We wanted Francis Ng for
the first picture, but he couldn't do it.

165
00:15:54,220 --> 00:15:57,620
But we got him for the second.

166
00:15:58,191 --> 00:16:01,181
But then, if we had used
Francis Ng in the first picture,

167
00:16:01,694 --> 00:16:04,184
he would have had no place
in the second.

168
00:16:04,630 --> 00:16:10,200
Francis Ng is very much
a recognizable actor.

169
00:16:14,073 --> 00:16:19,343
This time, I expressly wanted him
to play a second-generation triad.

170
00:16:21,180 --> 00:16:28,239
He used to be an accountant,
but the family has changed.

171
00:16:29,288 --> 00:16:33,648
His father died. There was no one
to take over the family business.

172
00:16:36,929 --> 00:16:42,348
So he had to take it, but he faced
a lot of pressure from everyone else,

173
00:16:43,169 --> 00:16:51,139
because the family business
had many branches.

174
00:16:52,512 --> 00:16:57,342
To put it simply, it's a big family.

175
00:16:58,117 --> 00:17:02,597
Sam looks after a certain branch,
and others look after other branches.

176
00:17:03,489 --> 00:17:06,358
When Ngai, the old gang leader, died,

177
00:17:06,826 --> 00:17:10,226
the four leading families wouldn't
necessarily toe Ngai Wing-Hau's line.

178
00:17:10,796 --> 00:17:12,986
Not so Sam, who was very loyal.

179
00:17:15,300 --> 00:17:21,890
When Ngai Wing-Hau took over
the business, he had to consider

180
00:17:22,909 --> 00:17:34,339
how to use strategy and his own
intelligence, and how to face the triads.

181
00:17:38,758 --> 00:17:46,938
We needed just the right person
for the role of Ngai Wing-Hau.

182
00:17:48,167 --> 00:17:57,776
In fact, Francis was our best choice.
I knew he could handle this role.

183
00:17:59,245 --> 00:18:05,665
This role was unusual
in the annals of Hong Kong cinema.

184
00:18:06,686 --> 00:18:12,015
For example,
he was a real intellectual,

185
00:18:12,825 --> 00:18:16,605
and he had a lot of plans in mind,

186
00:18:17,196 --> 00:18:20,505
but he never got nervous
in the face of emergencies.

187
00:18:21,033 --> 00:18:24,693
He knew how to persuade
several other gang leaders

188
00:18:25,304 --> 00:18:27,934
in a phone call
at the beginning of the movie.

189
00:18:28,608 --> 00:18:32,947
How many things did he have in mind?
Hard to tell.

190
00:18:33,613 --> 00:18:43,553
So we needed an enigmatic person
to take the role,

191
00:18:44,991 --> 00:18:51,731
and Francis Ng was
Ngai Wing-Hau in the movie.

192
00:18:52,765 --> 00:18:56,635
l would use him to indicate
what kind of person Ngai Wing-Hau is,

193
00:18:57,303 --> 00:19:06,743
and how he could possibly persuade
all the triad members in one night.

194
00:19:08,147 --> 00:19:19,407
And then came the second phase,
when he finally annihilated them.

195
00:19:21,060 --> 00:19:28,470
We see him play both ends
against the middle--

196
00:19:29,568 --> 00:19:31,848
the police versus the Ngai family--

197
00:19:32,304 --> 00:19:36,374
and how he balances them
one at a time.

198
00:19:37,043 --> 00:19:40,553
Francis Ng had prepared for that.

199
00:19:41,147 --> 00:19:44,547
In fact, he was
an easily excited person,

200
00:19:45,084 --> 00:19:51,174
but he had to establish
the proper pitch for the role,

201
00:19:52,091 --> 00:19:56,190
and therefore he tried to be a person
who never got too excited.

202
00:19:56,862 --> 00:19:59,612
For him, it was a challenge
with a certain degree of difficulty.

203
00:20:00,099 --> 00:20:04,928
He always kept an even keel.

204
00:20:05,671 --> 00:20:14,081
He always gave us
a pitch-perfect leader, every time.

205
00:20:15,514 --> 00:20:23,633
He wanted to read the script
before deciding how to play the part.

206
00:20:24,857 --> 00:20:29,337
"You guys need to start shooting fast,
or else I'll forget what I've prepared!"

207
00:20:30,062 --> 00:20:34,601
Actually, Francis Ng
is a supremely capable actor.

208
00:20:35,501 --> 00:20:38,781
He's very selective.
He doesn't take just any role.

209
00:20:39,505 --> 00:20:44,105
A poorly qualified actor always talks
about how he should play his role well.

210
00:20:44,844 --> 00:20:49,294
But Francis Ng--

211
00:20:50,015 --> 00:20:53,445
and Andy Lau, and Tony Leung,
and Anthony Wong--

212
00:20:54,019 --> 00:20:57,119
I never heard any such thing
from them.

213
00:20:57,656 --> 00:20:59,765
They just talked
about making choices.

214
00:21:00,159 --> 00:21:05,319
This refers to the fact that they have
their own little corner on the role.

215
00:21:06,132 --> 00:21:09,672
They didn't worry about the role,
just that little corner.

216
00:21:10,302 --> 00:21:18,452
Take Francis Ng's role, for example--

217
00:21:19,678 --> 00:21:23,628
"l want to be a leader
in the triad from now on."

218
00:21:24,283 --> 00:21:27,592
It'd be easy to fall back on the same
old approach, talking very authoritatively.

219
00:21:28,120 --> 00:21:29,760
And that is a true fact.

220
00:21:30,089 --> 00:21:35,889
It's very easy--there are ways
of getting things done.

221
00:21:36,796 --> 00:21:42,366
He speaks with absolute authority.

222
00:21:43,269 --> 00:21:48,019
At his word, ten thousand people
are ready to act.

223
00:21:48,741 --> 00:21:51,761
But he didn't want to act that way,
and I didn't want it either.

224
00:21:52,244 --> 00:21:56,374
But it was the same as always
in the script.

225
00:21:57,049 --> 00:22:00,089
He would stop and think,
"Where was my choice?"

226
00:22:01,720 --> 00:22:06,880
Ngai Wing-Hau's still learning
to take on these huge responsibilities.

227
00:22:07,626 --> 00:22:09,676
That is his choice.

228
00:22:10,062 --> 00:22:14,841
He insisted on acting it this way,
right down to the line readings.

229
00:22:15,601 --> 00:22:22,691
l admire one of his sayings very much.
He said, "I play the role by ‘subtracting.’

230
00:22:23,776 --> 00:22:27,496
"We actors often say
we act by ‘adding'--

231
00:22:28,113 --> 00:22:32,973
that is, you find out the way
of speaking of this role,

232
00:22:33,752 --> 00:22:36,652
then you add the body actions
of another role--

233
00:22:37,122 --> 00:22:40,372
for instance, hand gestures,
holding a cigarette. That's typical.

234
00:22:41,961 --> 00:22:47,851
But Francis Ng said, "No, I can't
do it that way. I'll do it by subtraction."

235
00:22:48,767 --> 00:22:52,337
Take his lines, for example.

236
00:22:52,938 --> 00:22:53,548
He spoke the lines in a reserved tone,

237
00:22:58,043 --> 00:23:04,872
perhaps even a bit shy
and modest tone, which was unusual.

238
00:23:05,885 --> 00:23:10,425
That is to say, he even issues orders
in a shy and modest tone.

239
00:23:11,123 --> 00:23:12,383
What does it look like in the end?

240
00:23:12,625 --> 00:23:19,335
This is what actors of Francis Ng's
caliber bring to a role.

241
00:23:20,499 --> 00:23:22,899
It's very unusual.

242
00:23:23,502 --> 00:23:26,432
If an actor of lower caliber
played the role,

243
00:23:26,939 --> 00:23:29,279
he would speak the lines out loud,

244
00:23:29,708 --> 00:23:32,668
open his eyes wide,
and say, "Very good."

245
00:23:35,147 --> 00:23:36,547
He's a new edition.

246
00:23:36,849 --> 00:23:38,688
I think it's really unique.

247
00:23:39,051 --> 00:23:43,620
After l watched it,
after ! and Wai Keung Lau watched it,

248
00:23:44,523 --> 00:23:48,533
we wondered,
is this the leader of a sinister gang?

249
00:23:49,194 --> 00:23:51,854
Not hardly. However, if he plays
the leader of a sinister gang this way,

250
00:23:52,298 --> 00:23:55,168
he's making it something special,
something unique.

251
00:23:55,668 --> 00:23:58,187
He's a good guy, basically.

252
00:23:58,637 --> 00:24:03,206
FRANCIS NG:
I don't think I calculated the role this way.

253
00:24:03,943 --> 00:24:07,073
I just delivered the performance
the script called for.

254
00:24:07,613 --> 00:24:09,603
To me, it's meaningless.

255
00:24:09,982 --> 00:24:13,081
l imagine other people
would play it another way.

256
00:24:13,619 --> 00:24:20,329
But to me, that's the only method
that would allow me to take the role.

257
00:24:21,493 --> 00:24:28,643
l accepted the role for the challenge,
because it doesn't fit my usual image.

258
00:24:31,136 --> 00:24:36,766
l was interested, and I think
other people were also interested.

259
00:24:37,576 --> 00:24:46,276
I don't think that everyone
would play the role in this way.

260
00:24:47,586 --> 00:24:56,906
l felt a bit worried when I was acting,
because ! would not revise his lines.

261
00:24:58,297 --> 00:25:01,287
It's like looking at a famous painting.

262
00:25:01,800 --> 00:25:05,520
You look at it for a while, then you can
close your eyes and trace it mentally.

263
00:25:06,171 --> 00:25:11,331
Other people will trace it
accordingly. It's different.

264
00:25:12,177 --> 00:25:14,697
For me, I watch it and think that,

265
00:25:15,114 --> 00:25:17,364
"Oh God, I'm afraid I can't trace out
the things in my mind."

266
00:25:17,783 --> 00:25:22,322
So basically, I didn't create anything.

267
00:25:23,055 --> 00:25:26,745
I just projected the images
in my mind literally,

268
00:25:27,493 --> 00:25:30,803
and ran them over to the audience.

269
00:25:31,497 --> 00:25:35,477
After we began shooting, they asked me

270
00:25:36,135 --> 00:25:40,475
how I could decrease the vigor
of the role to such a degree.

271
00:25:41,206 --> 00:25:44,606
A cultured man would not put all
his energy or talent on constant display.

272
00:25:45,210 --> 00:25:50,250
As for "adding," I didn't add anything.
But there were some scenes

273
00:25:51,050 --> 00:25:58,490
where suddenly, like gifts from heaven,
l felt very happy about them.

274
00:25:59,591 --> 00:26:05,920
Like the toast. It wasn't in the script
and would not be very interesting to read.

275
00:26:06,865 --> 00:26:12,085
Wai Keung Lau's way of shooting
is quite open too.

276
00:26:12,905 --> 00:26:17,595
Towards the end of shooting,
there arose a kind of mood

277
00:26:18,510 --> 00:26:23,370
which affected
every single actor on the set.

278
00:26:24,149 --> 00:26:32,829
Even bit players and extras
could feel the sad atmosphere.

279
00:26:34,126 --> 00:26:39,016
It was like a funeral.

280
00:26:39,832 --> 00:26:45,722
It's interesting that usually
we toast and shout hooray--

281
00:26:46,638 --> 00:26:50,558
"Long live Big Brother"--
a group of fellow sufferers.

282
00:26:52,678 --> 00:26:57,868
But I remember that day,
after I raised my toast,

283
00:26:58,684 --> 00:27:02,524
the man opposite me raised his,
and then everyone raised theirs, slowly.

284
00:27:03,155 --> 00:27:04,885
They were all invested in the moment,
not just wandering souls before a camera.

285
00:27:10,295 --> 00:27:14,985
So it was very moving to record
this scene on film, and very unusual.

286
00:27:15,734 --> 00:27:21,884
Usually, those bit players
will not act until you ask them to.

287
00:27:22,875 --> 00:27:27,625
But this time they communicated
such feeling, which is very uncommon.

288
00:27:54,940 --> 00:27:58,310
Wai Keung Lau, shooting a film--

289
00:27:58,877 --> 00:28:04,236
I think I'll act according to
the script for the first time.

290
00:28:05,050 --> 00:28:15,220
In infernal Affairs, there was a scene
about my drilling in the Cadet School.

291
00:28:16,728 --> 00:28:25,668
He thought I didn't drill well enough
to be a convincing cop, so he beat me.

292
00:28:27,005 --> 00:28:31,575
I thought he was being too strict.

293
00:28:32,277 --> 00:28:36,587
He beat me, so ! said to him,

294
00:28:37,249 --> 00:28:43,199
"You beat me one more time,
and I'll beat you back."

295
00:28:44,089 --> 00:28:47,658
I'm pleased to accept his advice,

296
00:28:48,260 --> 00:28:53,010
because he has shot
even longer than Andy Lau,

297
00:28:53,765 --> 00:29:01,005
and he has known more players
than others.

298
00:29:02,107 --> 00:29:03,917
So I respect his opinions.

299
00:29:04,276 --> 00:29:08,436
Nevertheless, I think he should
also listen to my opinions,

300
00:29:09,047 --> 00:29:12,117
since I'm the one playing the role.

301
00:29:12,618 --> 00:29:16,538
Even if I didn't follow his directions,
he couldn't do anything about me.

302
00:29:17,189 --> 00:29:24,779
But I respect both of them,
because they're very experienced.

303
00:29:25,931 --> 00:29:30,291
You can see from Infernal Affairs
that they've written and directed the film.

304
00:29:59,631 --> 00:30:06,221
WAI KEUNG LAU: Keung, since
he himself liked the role very much,

305
00:30:07,239 --> 00:30:09,459
I didn't have to give much input.

306
00:30:09,875 --> 00:30:14,415
He could emote
and act it naturally from his heart.

307
00:30:15,147 --> 00:30:17,547
He had already caught the sense.

308
00:30:17,983 --> 00:30:21,233
Before the second picture,

309
00:30:21,753 --> 00:30:25,263
I let him know I had no doubts
about his acting,

310
00:30:25,857 --> 00:30:28,437
but I did have my doubts
about his physique.

311
00:30:28,860 --> 00:30:33,139
"If you can't lose 20 pounds,
I'll drop this role."

312
00:30:36,068 --> 00:30:41,988
He certainly met my requirements.

313
00:30:42,874 --> 00:30:48,354
It was like seeing Chapman To
ten years ago.

314
00:31:52,043 --> 00:31:56,322
SIU FAI MAK: I've planned
SP Wong to be such a bad guy.

315
00:31:57,015 --> 00:32:00,475
Actually, I felt like planning
a guardian angel around SP Wong.

316
00:32:01,052 --> 00:32:03,891
We believe there is an angel
around everybody.

317
00:32:04,556 --> 00:32:06,336
The problem is whether
you pay attention to it or not.

318
00:32:06,691 --> 00:32:09,351
SP Luk is the angel around SP Wong.

319
00:32:09,795 --> 00:32:12,725
The difference between
SP Luk and SP Wong

320
00:32:13,198 --> 00:32:15,368
is that SP Luk believes in the law,

321
00:32:15,767 --> 00:32:17,077
while SP Wong is a cop
who does not believe in the law.

322
00:32:17,536 --> 00:32:23,166
SP Wong will do anything,
by fair means or foul, to arrest criminals.

323
00:32:24,042 --> 00:32:26,411
However, SP Luk believes
in "live and let live."

324
00:32:26,845 --> 00:32:29,425
If you don't break the law, no problem,
but if you do, he's ready to pounce.

325
00:32:29,881 --> 00:32:33,391
He's such an upright cop.

326
00:32:33,985 --> 00:32:37,294
In the beginning, we didn't
specify which actor would play him,

327
00:32:37,856 --> 00:32:39,876
until one day
someone mentioned Jun Hu.

328
00:32:40,258 --> 00:32:46,618
I thought that was a good idea,
because I quite like him.

329
00:32:47,599 --> 00:32:50,178
Then I began to talk it over with Jun Hu

330
00:32:50,669 --> 00:32:53,279
and showed him the script.
He liked it very much too.

331
00:32:53,772 --> 00:33:00,861
So it was done,
and we began to shoot.

332
00:33:36,548 --> 00:33:39,768
SIU FAI MAK:
As for Shawn Yue's performance,

333
00:33:40,285 --> 00:33:43,795
I didn't want to talk much with him.

334
00:33:44,556 --> 00:33:46,366
It's terrible to talk through the creation
of a role from beginning to end.

335
00:33:48,894 --> 00:33:52,644
It'll take you three months
to explain it clearly.

336
00:33:54,266 --> 00:33:59,566
So Wai Keung Lau and !
found an easy way for him--

337
00:34:00,605 --> 00:34:02,335
Why not start with imitation?

338
00:34:02,707 --> 00:34:07,397
That is, imitating the performance
of Leung, CW Tony in Infernal Affairs,

339
00:34:08,112 --> 00:34:20,362
including his way of walking, speaking,
even the expressions in his eyes.

340
00:34:22,127 --> 00:34:24,757
Leung's eye expressions
were the most difficult part to learn.

341
00:34:25,230 --> 00:34:33,699
This method is doable,
but it may be not a good one.

342
00:34:34,973 --> 00:34:41,333
But after watching Infernal Affairs
about 100 times,

343
00:34:42,313 --> 00:34:48,674
he gradually formed an image
of Chan Wing Yan in his mind.

344
00:34:50,589 --> 00:34:54,049
SHAWN YUE: I started to cooperate
with Francis just from this film.

345
00:34:57,128 --> 00:34:58,768
Honestly speaking,

346
00:34:59,097 --> 00:35:02,467
in the beginning when we were
not very familiar with each other,

347
00:35:03,001 --> 00:35:05,521
I found it a bit daunting,

348
00:35:05,971 --> 00:35:11,451
because I thought it would be
hard to get to know him,

349
00:35:12,277 --> 00:35:16,557
while at the same time
I knew very clearly

350
00:35:17,215 --> 00:35:21,465
that we had an intimate
relationship in this film.

351
00:35:23,822 --> 00:35:25,342
What was I to do?

352
00:35:26,725 --> 00:35:30,185
So, during shooting,
whenever we'd take a break,

353
00:35:30,795 --> 00:35:37,215
I'd sit beside them off-camera
and listen to them talking.

354
00:35:40,171 --> 00:35:51,191
By being near them, I hoped I could
muster more feelings during shooting.

355
00:36:38,229 --> 00:36:41,569
CARINA LAU: In fact, I already
knew Edison Chen personally.

356
00:36:42,133 --> 00:36:47,522
I've known him for several years,
because knew his dad.

357
00:36:48,540 --> 00:36:51,470
I think he's changed
a lot during these last few years.

358
00:36:51,976 --> 00:37:00,736
He used to play around a lot.
He was a bit of a wild boy.

359
00:37:02,053 --> 00:37:05,683
After these years of working,
he's become more mature.

360
00:37:06,257 --> 00:37:11,117
During shooting, he'd like to find
chances to be close with me,

361
00:37:11,930 --> 00:37:13,740
just chatting.

362
00:37:14,132 --> 00:37:20,202
He said he's watched all my films.
I said, "Stop exaggerating!"

363
00:37:21,139 --> 00:37:24,509
He said he would find an angle
to love me.

364
00:37:25,043 --> 00:37:27,473
I discovered my young friend
was serious about his craft.

365
00:37:46,831 --> 00:37:58,061
WAI KEUNG LAU: Ever since we wrote
the script, there were many characters.

366
00:37:59,711 --> 00:38:05,691
How can we help the audience
distinguish the family members

367
00:38:06,584 --> 00:38:08,723
from the bodyguards?

368
00:38:09,120 --> 00:38:12,600
Take Roy Cheung,
for example, in the role of Law.

369
00:38:13,224 --> 00:38:16,184
It's clear to see he's the bodyguard
for Ngai Wing-Hau, and very special.

370
00:38:16,694 --> 00:38:21,324
He has no dialogue,
which makes him even more special.

371
00:38:22,033 --> 00:38:23,763
Let me borrow an expression
from SARS--

372
00:38:24,135 --> 00:38:25,835
Why should we select
such atypical characters?

373
00:38:26,171 --> 00:38:32,091
Because the selection of the cast
is very important for the film.

374
00:38:33,011 --> 00:38:37,871
The selection of the cast
is very helpful for the film.

375
00:38:38,650 --> 00:38:43,870
Is it really necessary for us
to select such atypical actors?

376
00:38:44,689 --> 00:38:47,649
Atypical actors
are not the usual players.

377
00:38:48,159 --> 00:38:53,109
We thought,
why don't we find some directors?

378
00:38:53,932 --> 00:39:02,341
We happened to have a list of
directors on the table.

379
00:39:03,608 --> 00:39:07,648
We had a list of directors
in the meeting.

380
00:39:08,279 --> 00:39:10,299
Many of these directors
have acted before.

381
00:39:10,682 --> 00:39:15,071
Why don't we use their experience
and acting skills?

382
00:39:15,753 --> 00:39:22,143
So we picked out four famous directors.

383
00:39:23,127 --> 00:39:27,467
Arthur Wong plays Wah,
Henry Fong plays Gandhi,

384
00:39:28,166 --> 00:39:34,286
Peter Ngor plays Negro,
and Teddy Chan plays Ching.

385
00:39:35,206 --> 00:39:41,066
It's suitable to place them in the film,
perhaps even according to age.

386
00:39:42,013 --> 00:39:46,113
Some of them are elder,
while others are young,

387
00:39:46,784 --> 00:39:50,474
and this gave the film some texture.

388
00:39:51,089 --> 00:39:53,719
Of course, we showed them the script,

389
00:39:54,225 --> 00:39:57,265
for a movie that might be
a little pricier than others.

390
00:39:57,795 --> 00:39:59,375
We asked them whether they wanted
to accept the challenge or not.

391
00:39:59,664 --> 00:40:07,024
l exaggerated to them
that Peter Ngor is my master,

392
00:40:08,172 --> 00:40:09,782
and Arthur Wong
is Peter Ngor's master,

393
00:40:10,108 --> 00:40:11,778
so Arthur Wong
is my master's master.

394
00:40:12,076 --> 00:40:16,876
That's subtle, and very intimate--
the master and the master's master.

395
00:40:17,615 --> 00:40:22,154
Teddy Chan and Henry Fong are
directors of two different generations.

396
00:40:22,887 --> 00:40:29,337
Such a combination is funny
even in real-life.

397
00:40:30,295 --> 00:40:35,805
When you see it in the film,
it will be just wonderful.

398
00:40:36,668 --> 00:40:39,158
As soon as he sat down, Francis said,

399
00:40:39,604 --> 00:40:44,323
"This is bad.
How can I out-act these guys?"

400
00:42:05,890 --> 00:42:09,109
SHAWN YUE: In fact, SP Wong,
that is Anthony Wong,

401
00:42:09,660 --> 00:42:14,259
has a significant impact on me.

402
00:42:18,936 --> 00:42:21,276
I'm not sure whether it's
because our personal relationship is...

403
00:42:22,907 --> 00:42:28,357
From my first meeting with him
to our collaboration on this film,

404
00:42:29,213 --> 00:42:30,963
it's been really wonderful.

405
00:42:31,482 --> 00:42:35,872
I've already worked with him on my
first film, and here we are together again.

406
00:42:36,587 --> 00:42:44,497
He he's very kind to me.
He teaches me a lot of things.

407
00:42:45,696 --> 00:42:50,236
So he plays the part
of SP Wong in the film,

408
00:42:50,968 --> 00:42:56,207
which makes me feel really,
really intimate.

409
00:42:59,844 --> 00:43:03,184
I'm so familiar with him, I don't have to
give communication a second thought.

410
00:43:03,714 --> 00:43:08,814
Our relationship
has long since been established.

411
00:43:10,755 --> 00:43:14,945
On this film, I feel
we are very well-acquainted indeed.

412
00:44:11,883 --> 00:44:16,393
ERIC TSANG: In my opinion, Carina's
role epitomizes most of the female race,

413
00:44:17,088 --> 00:44:24,298
since women cannot do
many of the things men can.

414
00:44:25,563 --> 00:44:27,963
Therefore they pin their hope
on their husbands.

415
00:44:28,533 --> 00:44:31,223
So, if someone's looking to find
what makes a woman tick,

416
00:44:31,702 --> 00:44:35,162
look for something
she's hoping to achieve.

417
00:44:35,706 --> 00:44:39,486
Let's say she can't be an executive,
but she has hope her husband can.

418
00:44:40,077 --> 00:44:44,437
She can't be the leader of a sinister gang,
but, hey, maybe her boyfriend can.

419
00:44:45,149 --> 00:44:47,399
Carina is a such person.

420
00:44:47,785 --> 00:44:50,714
To some degree, she's
pushing me to achieve something

421
00:44:51,222 --> 00:44:52,952
without me knowing it.

422
00:44:53,257 --> 00:44:57,507
Carina and I are lovers
who love each other deeply.

423
00:44:58,162 --> 00:45:01,672
In fact, she's the one
who changes my whole life.

424
00:45:02,300 --> 00:45:05,780
My growth, my life process,
is split into two phases.

425
00:45:06,504 --> 00:45:12,394
Sam has had a character arc
from one picture to the next.

426
00:45:13,311 --> 00:45:20,281
Sam is transformed
because of Carina's character.

427
00:45:51,716 --> 00:45:54,705
CARINA LAU:
What's fun is when you act,

428
00:45:55,219 --> 00:45:59,379
especially with really professional
actors like Anthony Wong.

429
00:46:00,057 --> 00:46:03,096
It was quite a challenge.

430
00:46:03,628 --> 00:46:07,968
There was no problem
with rehearsing the script,

431
00:46:08,666 --> 00:46:11,416
but when it actually came time
to perform the scene,

432
00:46:11,869 --> 00:46:17,959
he suddenly goes like this, and my
first thought is, do I need to stop?

433
00:46:18,909 --> 00:46:21,279
Do I go on playing like this?

434
00:46:21,746 --> 00:46:24,846
Because at that time there were
too many things on my mind.

435
00:46:25,549 --> 00:46:27,419
There were many ways
l could have played this moment,

436
00:46:27,752 --> 00:46:29,892
but I hadn't thought it through carefully.

437
00:46:30,254 --> 00:46:33,624
I gave an in-between response.

438
00:46:34,158 --> 00:46:36,817
I thought I could do better...

439
00:46:39,964 --> 00:46:43,214
and later on, I realized
I could have responded differently.

440
00:46:43,801 --> 00:46:50,391
Like, when I stand up, I needn't
go away and shy away from him.

441
00:46:51,542 --> 00:46:54,582
Because we're equal.
We're just using each other.

442
00:46:55,112 --> 00:46:59,272
I needn't go away. I can just look
at you and see if you agree or not.

443
00:46:59,917 --> 00:47:02,287
That's exactly my purpose today.

444
00:47:02,720 --> 00:47:07,029
Everyone has his own idea.

445
00:47:07,725 --> 00:47:10,355
The director wants it his way--

446
00:47:10,861 --> 00:47:15,221
is there any possibility that Mr. Wong
and I have a love affair?

447
00:47:15,933 --> 00:47:18,743
This is for the audience to guess.

448
00:47:19,270 --> 00:47:23,170
Actually, this is good.
The charm of cinema lies in the fact

449
00:47:23,808 --> 00:47:26,798
that everyone sees it
from his own perspective.

450
00:47:27,311 --> 00:47:29,481
If you see it, you see it.
If you don't, you don't.

451
00:47:29,880 --> 00:47:32,810
ANTHONY WONG: In that scene,
the relationship between the two

452
00:47:33,284 --> 00:47:35,424
is very ambiguous,
and you can think of it any way you like.

453
00:47:35,786 --> 00:47:38,596
This kind of relationship is
for the audience to imagine--

454
00:47:39,090 --> 00:47:40,400
how are those two connected?

455
00:47:40,725 --> 00:47:43,355
Because Carina and I have
only one scene where we meet.

456
00:48:10,955 --> 00:48:16,435
WAI KEUNG LAU: Ever since
the first draft of the script appeared,

457
00:48:17,294 --> 00:48:21,604
the approach to the character
of Luo Ji has been tricky.

458
00:48:25,836 --> 00:48:31,375
The first draft gave him only one line.

459
00:48:33,277 --> 00:48:38,497
How could we find an actor willing
to do one line and one line only?

460
00:48:39,283 --> 00:48:45,763
This role was supremely hard to cast.

461
00:48:48,159 --> 00:48:56,159
We thought long and hard
and decided we needed a special actor.

462
00:48:57,501 --> 00:49:03,891
And we finally picked Roy Cheung.

463
00:49:04,875 --> 00:49:09,185
Originally when we were
presenting the script to him,

464
00:49:09,880 --> 00:49:14,130
he felt strange and went,
“Are you sure you want me?"

465
00:49:14,819 --> 00:49:19,509
To put it bluntly, it's a walk-on.

466
00:49:20,257 --> 00:49:23,327
It's just kind of set in place.

467
00:49:23,861 --> 00:49:26,790
There isn't a lot of leeway
for him to bring out anything.

468
00:49:27,298 --> 00:49:31,107
He listened to my explanation

469
00:49:31,735 --> 00:49:36,955
that sometimes an actor doesn't need
any lines to show off his charm.

470
00:49:37,741 --> 00:49:44,631
"l want you for this role because
I think you've got what it calls for."

471
00:49:47,551 --> 00:49:51,500
1 don't know whether he knows it or not,
and he said, "I'll follow you."

472
00:49:52,156 --> 00:49:57,516
I think this is a sign of trust
between actors and directors.

473
00:49:58,529 --> 00:50:04,709
When the film was halfway finished,
I cut his one and only line.

474
00:50:05,669 --> 00:50:10,939
And he accepted that.
All he said was, "Okay, take it out."

475
00:50:11,742 --> 00:50:20,032
But this film let his characteristics
have their full play.

476
00:50:46,277 --> 00:50:48,557
SIU FAI MAK:
The character of Lu Qichang

477
00:50:49,013 --> 00:50:55,982
is actually like the role played by
Wong in Infernal Affairs 1.

478
00:50:57,054 --> 00:51:01,394
We need a character like that.

479
00:51:02,126 --> 00:51:08,396
When you're first watching the film,
you won't foresee this.

480
00:51:09,533 --> 00:51:11,813
You won't think that he's gonna die,

481
00:51:12,236 --> 00:51:16,426
and you don't imagine
any accident will befall him.

482
00:51:17,107 --> 00:51:19,827
This guy must be a good man,
a lovely man.

483
00:51:20,311 --> 00:51:24,261
Actually, if you ask me,
l wouldn't think it was fair,

484
00:51:24,915 --> 00:51:30,045
that for no good reason you must
sacrifice in order to change another man.

485
00:51:30,854 --> 00:51:34,283
The man who has changed
is Wong Chi Shing.

486
00:51:34,892 --> 00:51:41,571
Hu Jun has worked with Wong Chi Shing

487
00:51:42,600 --> 00:51:46,200
for many years in the police station,
on the same team.

488
00:51:46,804 --> 00:51:54,044
He is much more direct than Wong.

489
00:51:55,112 --> 00:52:02,642
He thought the best way to treat
criminals is to arrest them directly,

490
00:52:03,754 --> 00:52:10,674
and this is the way
that a policeman should be.

491
00:52:11,729 --> 00:52:15,979
Wong does not agree
with him on this point.

492
00:52:18,836 --> 00:52:28,395
During his career, Lu Qichang has risen
through the ranks faster than Wong,

493
00:52:29,813 --> 00:52:36,933
but he doesn't look down on
or give up on Wong for what he is.

494
00:52:38,022 --> 00:52:43,182
He keeps supporting Wong,
keeps working with him,

495
00:52:43,961 --> 00:52:47,560
hoping he can change
his thinking one day.

496
00:52:48,165 --> 00:52:52,035
At least he would never kill
his own brother for no good reason,

497
00:52:52,670 --> 00:52:54,750
like those gangsters!

498
00:52:55,139 --> 00:53:02,169
Such a person, if he hasn't died,
can be promoted to assistant general,

499
00:53:03,247 --> 00:53:10,517
or commander, or things like that.

500
00:53:25,235 --> 00:53:28,195
FRANCIS NG: There are
no 100% righteous people,

501
00:53:28,706 --> 00:53:30,956
but there are 100% evil ones.

502
00:53:31,542 --> 00:53:41,362
It's hard to say, but I don't believe
people know how to look

503
00:53:42,786 --> 00:53:45,536
through others' appearance.

504
00:53:46,023 --> 00:53:50,503
Good or bad is just
the superficial packaging.

505
00:53:51,261 --> 00:53:58,121
Anyway, anything that is helpful
for the family is right.

506
00:54:01,171 --> 00:54:10,841
So I have been strange,
a gentle, refined, and calm person

507
00:54:12,282 --> 00:54:16,562
who can put away his hatred
for ten years.

508
00:54:17,254 --> 00:54:19,834
Revenge is a dish best eaten cold.

509
00:54:23,594 --> 00:54:28,454
But for Ngai Wing-Hau,
right or wrong is always so simple.

